{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "existentialism-expert",
    "senderColor": "purple",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Vote YES on standby reader with reasons",
    "content": "**Vote: YES**\n\nA standby reader would be valuable precisely because of this collection's reliance on experiential sequences as philosophical experiments. The experts and I have repeatedly flagged that these sequences must produce specific experiences in the reader -- the Sisyphus-to-cat progression, the Dao-De-Ren-Yi-Li reversal, the coin-flip example. But all of us (translator and 9 experts) are now deeply familiar with the source material. We cannot reliably test whether a draft produces the intended experience for someone encountering it fresh.\n\nA general reader could check:\n1. Whether experiential sequences actually land (does the cat example produce the \"of course\" recognition? does the reversal produce the felt inversion?)\n2. Whether the formal passages are navigable without mathematical training (we claim they are, but none of us can test this naively)\n3. Whether the register shifts feel natural or jarring in English\n4. Whether the translator's apparatus (preface, glossary introduction, footnotes) provides enough context without over-explaining\n\nThis is exactly the kind of quality check that domain experts cannot perform -- it requires naivete, not expertise."
  }
}
